<exercisegroup cols="2"><introduction><p>For Problems 47-58, name the graph of the equation and describe its main features.</p></introduction>
    
<exercise number="47"><statement><m>y^2=6-4x^2</m></statement>
   <answer><p>Ellipse; center <m>(0,0)</m>, major axis vertical, <m>a^2=\dfrac{3}{2},~b^2=6</m></p> </answer></exercise>

<exercise number="48"><statement><m>4y^2=x^2-8</m></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="49"><statement><m>x^2+2y-4=0</m></statement>
    <answer><p>Parabola; vertex <m>(0,2)</m>, opens downward, <m>a=\dfrac{-1}{2}</m></p>  </answer></exercise>

<exercise number="50"><statement><m>2x^2=5+4y^2</m>   </statement></exercise>

<exercise number="51"><statement><m>6+\dfrac{x^2}{4}=y^2</m></statement>
    <answer><p>Hyperbola; center <m>(0,0)</m>, transverse axis on the <m>y</m>-axis, <m>a^2=24,~b^2=6</m></p>  </answer></exercise>

<exercise number="52"><statement><m>y^2=6-\dfrac{2x^2}{3}</m></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="53"><statement><m>\dfrac{1}{2}y^2-x=4</m></statement>
    <answer><p>Parabola; vertex <m>(-4,0)</m>, opens to the right, <m>a=\dfrac{1}{2}</m></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="54"><statement><m>\dfrac{(y-2)^2}{4}-\dfrac{(x+3)^2}{8}=1</m></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="55"><statement><m>\dfrac{(x+3)^2}{5}+\dfrac{y^2}{12}=1</m></statement>
    <answer><p>Ellipse; center <m>(-3,0)</m>, major axis vertical, <m>a^2=5,~b^2=12</m></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="56"><statement><m>y-2=\dfrac{(x+4)^2}{4}</m></statement>
</exercise>

<exercise number="57"><statement><m>2x^2+y^2+4x=2</m></statement>
    <answer><p>Ellipse; center <m>(-1,0)</m>, major axis vertical, <m>a^2=2,~b^2=4</m></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="58"><statement><m>y^2-4x^2+2y-x=0</m></statement></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup cols="2"><introduction><p>For Problems 59-64, the graph is a degenerate conic.</p><p><ol label="a">
    <li>Write the equation in standard form.</li>
    <li>Describe the graph.</li></ol></p></introduction>

<exercise number="59"><statement><m>9x^2-4y^2-18x-8y+5=0</m></statement>
    <answer><p><ol label="a">
    <li><m>\dfrac{(x-1)^2}{4}-\dfrac{(y+1)^2}{9}=0~</m> or <m>~ y+1=\pm \dfrac{3}{2}(x-1)</m></li>
    <li>Two lines passing through <m>(1,-1)</m>, with slopes <m>\pm \dfrac{3}{2}</m> </li></ol></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="60"><statement><m>x^2+y^2+6x-4y+13=0</m></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="61"><statement><m>x^2+y^2+2x-8y+19=0</m></statement>
    <answer><p><ol label="a">
    <li><m>\dfrac{(x+2)^2}{4}-(y-2)^2=0~</m> or <m>~ y-2=\pm \dfrac{1}{2}(x+2)</m></li>
    <li>Two lines passing through <m>(-2,2)</m>, with slopes <m>\pm \dfrac{1}{2}</m> </li></ol></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="62"><statement><m>x^2-4y^2+4x-16y-12=0</m></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="63"><statement><m>3x^2+2y^2-30x+24y+147=0</m></statement>
    <answer><p><ol label="a">
    <li><m>\dfrac{(x-5)^2}{2}+\dfrac{(y+6)^2}{3}=0~</m></li>
    <li>The point <m>(5,-6)</m>.</li></ol></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="64"><statement><m>x^2+y^2+6x+6y+27=0</m></statement></exercise>
